<subSubSection id="77C58AFCA6333A53B7D11E77A8DFD54A" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" type="notes">
<paragraph id="E80431004ABEC292DB22F4E1B21F9FC9" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="551B7746CB27DE666C7F511EEFE5233E" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
Elevating 
<taxonomicName id="FCA7B9E52B930612EB76CF89E963BA3C" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon fremontii subsp. var. var. glabrescens" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="fremontii" subSpecies="var." variety="glabrescens">Penstemon fremontii var. glabrescens</taxonomicName>
to a species using the epithet 
<taxonomicName id="073A1BAC1411327D9E97BE48B4A4A63B" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="glabrescens" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glabrescens">
<emphasis id="73A19F84D2D5D2EB76C9B0FADA4D64AC" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">glabrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not possible because 
<taxonomicName id="04E8D4598E1367AD9BBA89EFB75E00CF" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon glabrescens" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glabrescens">
<emphasis id="0A9335591FEA4F8B49A4B5F038548440" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Penstemon glabrescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is already occupied (
<bibRefCitation id="D9AD80B3D1D980FFAFE53D96E8846395" author="Pennell, FW" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" pagination="313 - 381" refId="B12" refString="Pennell, FW, 1920. Scrophulariaceae of the central Rocky Mountain states. Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 20: 313 - 381" title="Scrophulariaceae of the central Rocky Mountain states." volume="20" year="1920">Pennell 1920</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E5DE666B55D93C1FBABA79FA6E80ED52" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="04E47E6AF7626A7CE65BF5D029D5C2A5" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="81FBEC6C253D5D70FBA761CCCEB8F09C" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="A389808E7F8AD46EFE8AD1741B684834" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon luculentus" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="luculentus">
<emphasis id="794EEB11E4A16BBE7CD4A10720D60F25" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Penstemon luculentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the Latin &quot; 
<taxonomicName id="722F71293099A8CF11C0D3371F88327A" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="luculentus" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="luculentus">
<emphasis id="8567B5574663F06D26F45CE0B36E0A0E" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">luculentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
,&quot; meaning brilliant or bright. The name was chosen to reflect the brilliant blue flower color, which is particularly striking in the field contrasting against the whitish or tan shale background typically associated with the species (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="40E5701701AEF2BDEF3B62ADC677262F" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A Penstemon luculentus in its commonly found native whitish or tan shale habitat B An individual Penstemon luculentus plant growing in its typical shale habitat." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.63.7952.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/89415" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">1A, B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="2D531043CCCA639DEBDA3148F26E95EC" ID-Zenodo-Dep="978727" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.63.7952.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/89415" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" start="Figure 1" startId="F1">
<paragraph id="7110A64FFE2D515204CFE807451CD647" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis id="08AE9EBCFB58A192F9F8C892CFBEDDBC" bold="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Figure 1.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="9693F4B0CDD28B53A06016FF4540AC69" bold="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">A</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="389DF290AD78346E8F4F2683CB284FCA" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon luculentus" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="luculentus">
<emphasis id="43314E7184F7E436E2D12A11F47FAA19" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Penstemon luculentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its commonly found native whitish or tan shale habitat 
<emphasis id="943CF8AEC7A9B936EA106EB43A256A9D" bold="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">B</emphasis>
An individual 
<taxonomicName id="F7307A18ACA38C23A1F9B5703AEA06CA" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon luculentus" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="luculentus">
<emphasis id="C1D1E974A1D5B82E38A3AD41A2A54088" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Penstemon luculentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plant growing in its typical shale habitat.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E3C25014B82CF63C7E7553050F15C089" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="496FA2B158CB84E05B8F52305601B55B" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E02001B44D5B40A07756349105DAA640" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="2A41A55CD020F283E29629257851F9DB" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon luculentus" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="luculentus">
<emphasis id="A5A4835F2317A9E087FF429EFBF871FE" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Penstemon luculentus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(≡ 
<taxonomicName id="E7C68B31A95DCD2ECBADC2972A29815B" authorityName="Johnson &amp; Stevens &amp; Johnson &amp; Robbins &amp; Anderson &amp; Ricks &amp; Farley" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Scrophulariaceae" genus="Penstemon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Penstemon fremontii subsp. var. var. glabrescens" order="Lamiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="fremontii" subSpecies="var." variety="glabrescens">Penstemon fremontii var. glabrescens</taxonomicName>
) grows almost exclusively on steep slopes composed of Green River shale or sometimes intermixed with sandstone fragments from overlying strata. It is locally common on road cuts. It occurs primarily within the Piceance drainage with populations occurring abundantly on exposed shale along Piceance Creek and the adjacent tributaries, including the Yellow Creek drainage in Rio Blanco Co., CO. (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="47D681B586CCA3B1225BADF0A20BB63E" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Map showing known distribution of Penstemon luculentus in Rio Blanco and Garfield counties Colorado." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.63.7952.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/89416" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">2</figureCitation>
). It also occurs on shale slopes of the Roan Creek drainage in Garfield Co., CO. The Colorado Natural Heritage Program (CNHP) gives this taxon a global rank of G3G4T2 and a state rank of S2 due to threats from gas and oil drilling throughout its habitat in the Piceance Basin (
<bibRefCitation id="E192C99745454F5FE45CBD88FBAB1FB2" author="CNHP" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" publicationUrl="http://www.cnhp.colostate.edu/download/projects/rareplants/guide.asp?id=24426" refId="B3" refString="CNHP, 2015. http://www.cnhp.colostate.edu/download/projects/rareplants/guide.asp?id=24426 [accessed 18.12.2015]" url="http://www.cnhp.colostate.edu/download/projects/rareplants/guide.asp?id=24426" year="2015">CNHP 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The ranking of G3G4 indicates a status between vulnerable and apparently secure. The rank of S2 specifies a state status of &quot;imperiled - at high risk of extinction due to very restricted range, very few populations (often 20 or fewer), recent and widespread declines, or other factors&quot; (
<bibRefCitation id="2041E5089EA3F657B58C6439DFD7CCD2" author="Rondeau, RK" journalOrPublisher="The Nature Conservancy by the Colorado Natural Heritage Program, Colorado State Univeristy, Fort Collins, Colorado" pageId="8" pageNumber="55" refId="B14" refString="Rondeau, RK, Handwerk, J, Simers, L, Granau, , Pague, C, 2011. The state of Colorado's biodiversity. The Nature Conservancy by the Colorado Natural Heritage Program, Colorado State Univeristy, Fort Collins, Colorado" title="The state of Colorado's biodiversity" year="2011">Rondeau et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Currently oil and gas drilling have not had a noticeable impact on its populations, but that could change if oil extraction begins to include the mining of oil shale.
</paragraph>
